Introduction

Prosper Marketplace, Inc. is a San Francisco, California-based company in the peer-to-peer lending industry. Prosper Funding LLC, one of its subsidiaries, operates Prosper.com, a website where individuals can either invest in personal loans or request to borrow money. (soure: Wikipedia )

Today we shall take a look at a Dataset with information for over 100K loans processed by Prosper ranging from 2005 to 2014.

Although CreditGrade has only a fraction of the whole dataset as non-null, i would like to use it for some investigations, going to setup a grading ordered Cat.

ProsperRatings can be visualized here: Prosper. Also going to setup an ordered Cat, despite there being a numerical column for it, because i believe Letter gradings are more meaningful than Numeric gradings in presentations (at least for this case).

Also worth noting that we should change columns to all lower case to make life easier, not having to type uppercase all the time and removing some () information.

Change some columns to datetime so we can perform some analysis over time periods

Drop some columns with personal information or identification that we can't use in our analysis (ex: keeping State is useful to group by states but we have no need for MemberKey).

A very small intersection of data without either CreditGrade or ProsperRating, should be removed since it represents a very small fraction of our dataset and I want to be consistent with the dataset.

Should group together all the Past Dues into one.

Further Wrangling

Ordering Ratings

Putting order to our ratings so our visuals come out nicer

In [27]:
ordinal_var_dict = {'creditgrade': ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA'],
                    'prosperrating': ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
        ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                    categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
        df[var] = df[var].astype(ordered_var)

Loan Months¶

We have a useful column already that is "loanmonthsinceorigination", we might want to use it but capped out at the term amount if the loan is Completed or equivalent. Also rename to just loanmonths.

In [28]:
df.loc[df['loanstatus'].str.contains('Past Due',na=False), 'loanstatus'] = 'Past Due'

df.rename(columns={'loanmonthssinceorigination':'loanmonths'},inplace=True)

finishedloans = ['Completed','Chargedoff','Defaulted','Cancelled']
for loan in finishedloans:
    df.loc[df.loanstatus == loan, 'loanmonths'] = df.term

Univariate Exploration

To get familiar with our data, lets take a quick look at some plots, starting off with Credit Grades and Prosper Ratings, also what the typical loan amount looks like and the current status of loans in the dataset.

In [29]:

            order = df.loanstatus.value_counts().index)

These 4 plots should get us started with a feeling of how to approach our questions for the remainder of the data available to us.

The top 2 bar charts show us the distribution according to grades (Credit and Prosper), ordered by worst to best grade. Both charts are unimodal and not so skewed, with more "middle" grades than anything else. Important to note that Credit Grades had an extra NC grading possibility which represented a very small group, it was added into the HR group. This distribution caught me a bit off guard, as i expected much less counts in the higher ranked grades.

Our histogram of Loan amounts is very Right-skewed, with multiple peaks that appear to be around the multiples of 5k, especially at the 5k, 10k and 15k marks. Bins were adjusted to $1k steps. The amount of loans over the 25k mark make me want to not use them further as they are clearly outliers.

Our final bar chart show us the count of Loans divided into their current Status. Ordered by Count Descending. The data was tidied up to group all the Past Due categories into one. Cancelled was removed (only had 5 cases) and FinalPaymentProgress was encorporated to current.

Next let's take a quick look at where our Borrowers come from.

Here we gain a bit of insight that a large portion of the Borrower's come from CA, which makes sense since Prosper is a Californian based company. After that it seems to be spread out around the eastcoast but nothing special.

Bivariate Exploration

To continue our observations into our dataset, I believe it would be interesting to take a better look at how the Status of our loans are divided.

In [31]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
ax = sb.countplot(data = df, x = 'loanstatus', hue = 'creditgrade',palette='ocean_r')
ax.legend(loc = 1)
ax.set_xlabel('Loan Statuses by Credit Grade')
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
ax = sb.countplot(data = df, x = 'loanstatus', hue = 'prosperrating',palette='ocean_r')
ax.legend(loc = 2)
ax.set_xlabel('Loan Statuses by Prosper Rating');

Interesting to note on the Left Plot, which uses the Credit Grade and apparently was phased out for Prospers own Prosper Rating since there are no longer Current or Past Due Loans, is that the Count of HR loans Completed is almost the same as Chargedoff and only slightly higher than Defaulted.

Our Right Plot, which uses the current Prosper Rating system, contains all our Current loans for the Dataset. Looking at only Current we see a sort of distribution that resembles our previous Univariate Countplot of Prosper Ratings. That is expected since we expect to see current loans to resemble a bit our distribution of Ratings. But when we look at all the other Status Categories, we notice a trend of very low AA, A and high HR,E counts for the "negative" outcome categories (i.e Defaulted and Charged Off). This is also expected, since consumers with lower credit ratings should theoretically have higher chances of defaulting.

We can also take a look at how the loan amount varies according to the Borrowers Rating.

It is common knowledge that a better Credit grade, or Prosper Rating in this case too, gives you access to better APR's. A set of Violin plots should allow us to take a good look into this.

The Violin Plots bring us an Amazing insight of how the APR correlates to the Ratings. On Credit Grades the violins still had some tails/whiskers that balanced a bit the distribution, but on Prosper Ratings the APR obtained by HR rated clients was completly blown away by the APR obtained by AA rated.

If you were to guess the main factor that decides if a person can pay off a loan or not, Income has to be it. Afterall, a person making 1k dollars/month will find it much harder to pay off a 10k dollars Loan than a person who makes 20k dollars/month. From here on i shall start looking at Loans that have been closed already, either with a positive outcome (i.e Completed) or a negative outcome (i.e Chargedoff or Defaulted). Also, i shall filter out people who make over 20K dollars/month because they are not representing very well the rest of the dataset.

In [47]:
#creating 2 df's for positive and negative outcome of closed loans, limiting to declared monthly income 20000, verifiable
positive_outcome = df.loc[(df.loanstatus=="Completed")&(df.statedmonthlyincome<20000)&(df.incomeverifiable==True)]
negative_outcome = df.loc[(df.loanstatus=="Chargedoff")|(df.loanstatus=="Defaulted")
                          &(df.statedmonthlyincome <20000)&(df.incomeverifiable==True)]

#Fitting a Linear Regression
xseq = np.linspace(0, 30000)
b, a = np.polyfit(positive_outcome.loanoriginalamount,positive_outcome.statedmonthlyincome, deg=1)
b2, a2 = np.polyfit(negative_outcome.loanoriginalamount,negative_outcome.statedmonthlyincome, deg=1)


#taking 1000 samples for plotting from each to not clutter too much, since they have 34k and 16k rows, respectively
positive_sample = positive_outcome.sample(1000)
negative_sample = negative_outcome.sample(1000)

#plotting in blue and orange instead of blue and red for colorblind visibility
plt.figure(figsize=(20,12))
plt.scatter(x='loanoriginalamount',y='statedmonthlyincome',alpha=0.2,data=positive_sample,marker='o')
plt.plot(xseq, a + b * xseq, color="steelblue", lw=2.5)
plt.scatter(x='loanoriginalamount',y='statedmonthlyincome',alpha=0.2,data=negative_sample,marker='x',color='orange')
plt.plot(xseq, a2 + b2 * xseq, color='orange', lw=2.5)
plt.xlabel("Loan Amount ($)")
plt.ylabel("Monthly Income ($)")
plt.legend(['Positive Outcome','Positive Fitted Regression','Negative Outcome','Negative Fitted Regression'])
plt.title('Loan Amount vs Monthly Income with Linear Regressions')
plt.ylim(0,20000)
plt.xlim(0,26000);

Although the Scatter part of the plot didn't relay much information, once fitted and plotted a linear regression we can observe 2 important pieces of information:

  1. Positive correlation between Monthly income and Loan amount, which is expected but
  2. The Fitted line for Negative Outcomes stays 'underneath' the Positive Outcomes fitted line. This shows us that for the same loan amount taken out, the Borrowers that didn't manage to pay the loan back in order had, on average, ALWAYS a lower verified Monthly Income. The lines should cross somewhere off the limits of the graph but that is outside of normal cases for our data.

Now, along with Monthly income, it should also be valid to look into the Debt to income ratio since people who have a lot of debt also should struggle to pay off their loans.

And for fun we shall see how these compare by our 20 most active States in the dataset

Multiple Variable Regression Model

Now that we took a look into what seems to correlate with what, time to try to create a function that shall predict the probability of a borrower having a positive or negative outcome with their loan. For this we shall use the data from Positive and Negative, assign a 1 for positive and 0 for negative, then train a multi variable regression and try to apply that to our data that has no outcome yet (i.e the loans are still open).

In [57]:
#once again we shall limit to verifiable income and 20000/month, to remove most of the outliers
p_outcome_df = df.loc[(df.loanstatus=="Completed")&(df.statedmonthlyincome <20000)&(df.incomeverifiable==True)].copy()
n_outcome_df = df.loc[(df.loanstatus=="Chargedoff")|(df.loanstatus=="Defaulted")
                     &(df.statedmonthlyincome <20000)&(df.incomeverifiable==True)].copy()
no_outcome_df = df.loc[(df.loanstatus=="Current")|(df.loanstatus=="Past Due")
                      &(df.statedmonthlyincome <20000)&(df.incomeverifiable==True)].copy()

p_outcome_df['outcome'] = 1
n_outcome_df['outcome'] = 0
outcome_df = pd.merge(p_outcome_df,n_outcome_df,how='outer')

#dropping nulls so we can fit a regression
outcome_df = outcome_df[outcome_df.borrowerapr.notnull()]
outcome_df = outcome_df[outcome_df.debttoincomeratio.notnull()]
outcome_df = outcome_df[outcome_df.statedmonthlyincome.notnull()]
outcome_df = outcome_df[outcome_df.loanoriginalamount.notnull()]

y = outcome_df['outcome']
x = outcome_df[['borrowerapr','debttoincomeratio','statedmonthlyincome','loanoriginalamount']]

x = sm.add_constant(x) # adding a constant
 
model = sm.OLS(y, x).fit()
outcome_df.outcome = model.predict(x)
model.summary()

Conclusions

Through our visualizations we were able to identify the distribution between Credit Grades and Prosper Ratings, along with the typical Loan amount and identified our demographic. Then we saw how the Loan amount was different according to said Grades and Ratings, along with the obtained APR. Diggin further we discovered the correlation between Monthly income and Debt to Income Ratio with the scenarios of Positive or Negative outcomes for the Loans, along with a general look at how Loan amount and Monthly Income faced off head to head.

Knowing that, we plotted Estimated Losses and Returns and determined that they were correlated to APR and, seeing how APR obviously impacts a persons ability to pay off a loan, we chose to not use them in our regression, staying only with the Borrower APR. Putting everything together we were able to create a multi variable linear Regression that allows us to predict, quite precisely, the probabilities of the loans being paid off.
